    "rawTitle": "### Vegan Caribbean Sweet Potato Pudding (**DESSERT**)",
    "rawBody": "- **URL:** https://healthiersteps.com/vegan-jamaican-sweet-potato-pudding/ ✓ VERIFIED *(Michelle Blackwood, RN / Healthier Steps — Jamaica-born Caribbean food blogger, fully vegan + gluten-free, 4.99/61 votes (exceptionally well-tested). Recipe is naturally vegan from the ground up — uses canned coconut milk in place of dairy and an extra coconut-milk custard topping added at the halfway-bake mark for the signature golden custard top. The Jamaican baking style is called \"hell a top, hell a bottom, and hallelujah in the middle\" — both rack positions on hot, custard set in the middle. Notable: best made with the white-flesh batata variety (West Indian sweet potato), but readers report success with American sweet potato if you double the flour. AP flour also works as a sub for the gluten-free flour per reader testing.)*\n\n  **Recipe** (12 slices, per Michelle Blackwood): 2 lb sweet potatoes (preferably batata; if using American sweet potato, double the flour), 1 × 14 oz can coconut milk, 1 cup coconut palm sugar, 1 tsp freshly grated ginger, 1 tsp vanilla, 1 cup gluten-free AP flour or brown rice flour (or regular AP), ½ tsp cinnamon (optional), ½ tsp nutmeg (optional), ¼ tsp sea salt. **Custard topping:** ½ cup coconut milk + 1 tbsp coconut sugar + ¼ tsp vanilla + pinch cinnamon. Preheat 375°F, grease 9\" round pan. Peel + chop sweet potatoes; grate or process in a food processor (add a little of the coconut milk to help it process). Transfer to a large bowl; add coconut milk, sugar, ginger, vanilla, spices, salt; stir in flour to form a mostly-smooth batter. Pour into pan; bake 45 min. Whisk custard topping ingredients; pour evenly over the half-baked pudding; return to oven another 45 min until top is golden brown. Total: 1 hr 45 min. 166 cal/slice.\n- **Description:** Slow-baked grated-sweet-potato pudding with coconut milk, ginger, and warming spices, finished with a coconut-milk custard topping that bakes into a golden custard glaze. Sliced like a cake, plated warm with a coconut-rum cream drizzle or vegan coconut ice cream. The classic \"hell a top, hell a bottom, and hallelujah in the middle\" Jamaican pudding (the traditional name for the dual-rack baking method), naturally vegan.\n- **Wholesale food cost:** $1.20 / serving · **Menu price:** $7–10 / $9–12 with rum cream\n- **Weight:** 130 g (slice) · **Calories:** 166 · **Protein:** 2 g · **Time:** 15 min prep + 1 hr 30 min bake · **Servings:** 12 / 9\" pan\n- **Restaurant difficulty:** **Easy** — bake whole, slice, warm in salamander per ticket. Holds 1–2 days well-wrapped at room temp; freezes excellently.\n- **Tags:** 🥘 Bulk-Prep · ⚡ Fast-Service\n\n| Sub | Effect | Cost delta |\n|---|---|---|\n| Batata (white-flesh Jamaican sweet potato — Michelle's default) | Most authentic — sold at West Indian, Asian, African groceries; also Walmart | baseline ($1.20) |\n| American sweet potato (orange-flesh) — double the flour | More widely available; brighter color | flat |\n| Purple sweet potato | Striking color, premium plating | +$0.40 |\n| Add coconut-rum cream drizzle (per-ticket) | Premium presentation | +$0.30 → menu $9–12 |\n| Pair with vegan coconut ice cream | À la mode | +$0.80 → menu $9–12 |",
